One of the many interesting talks I attended at AGU 2018 was an introduction to the [IIASA Community Water Model](https://cwatm.github.io/) given by Peter Burek. The model is implemented in Python and is free and open source under the terms of the GNU General Public Licence (version 3). This post explores the program in more detail.

# Program structure

CWATM follows an object oriented design which employs the PCRaster dynamic model concept.

The root directory contains a number of files. The main program is contained in cwatm.py, which defines class `CWATModel` and a function `CWATMexe()` to execute the model. Class `CWATModel` is a subclass of the `CWATModel_ini` and `CWATModel_dyn` base classes (Python allows multiple inheritance), which are defined in files cwatm_initial.py and cwatm_dynamic.py, respectively. Class `CWATModel_ini` performs non-temporal initialization procedures while `CWATModel_dyn` performs the time loop. When a Python file is run as the main program (e.g. simon@yamunotri\$ python cwatm.py on the command line), the Python interpreter will set a number of special variables. One of these is to set the variable `__name__` to `__main__`, which means that the main script is interpreted by Python as a module with the name `__main__`. On the other hand, if the file is being imported from another module the `__name__` variable will be set to the module's name (https://stackoverflow.com/questions/419163/what-does-if-name-main-do). Hence, as is usual for Python programs, the main program cwatm.py contains the control structure `if __name__ == __main__` and a series of commands which parse any command line arguments (i.e. any arguments after the file name) and runs the function CWATMexe(). The control structure is not in a function and hence the variables defined therein are global variables to which all scopes have access (https://stackoverflow.com/questions/4775579/main-and-scoping-in-python). \\

The management_modules directory contains a number of files which define various functions to coordinate the model run. This includes functions to configure the model (configuration.py; parse_configuration), perform runtime checks (checks.py), manipulate data (data_handling.py), define global variables and check the system requirements are met (globals.py), provide runtime information (messages.py), write output (output.py), handle timestepping (timestep.py) and augment some PCRaster functionality (improvepcraster.py, replace_pcr.py). Function parse_configuration (configuration.py) is essentially a wrapper around ConfigParser (https://docs.python.org/2/library/configparser.html), but includes an extension ExtParser which conveniently enables the user to use file handles to specify the paths of input variables. This means that users only need to change the handles rather than every single filepath. \\

Subdirectory hydrological_modules contains various files which each define a class to represent specific hydrological processes (e.g. capillary rise, evaporation). Each class definition includes 'initial' and 'dynamic' methods. 

## Time stepping

Time stepping is handled by classes defined in the PCRaster Python extension. Note that CWATM includes the relevant PCRaster class definitions in its source code (presumably to ensure that PCRaster version changes do not affect CWATM) so it should not be necessary for users to install PCRaster on their computers in order to use the model. Parsing the configuration file instantiates dateVar... (?) After parsing the configuration file, the main function (CWATMexe) initializes class CWATModel_ini. This class inherits from class DynamicModel (defined in pcraster2/dynamicPCRasterBase.py), which includes a number of getter/setter methods for time-based attributes. The DynamicFramework constructor expects three arguments: userModel, which must implement the PCRaster dynamic model concept (in effect it should inherit from DynamicModel class), firstTimeStep and lastTimeStep. The CWATModel_ini class instance (variable CWATM in function CWATMexe) is supplied to the DynamicFramework constructor as argument userModel, while firstTimeStep and lastTimeStep are retrieved from the global variable dateVar (management_modules/globals.py). The __init__ method of DynamicFramework assigns argument userModel to class attribute _userModel and firstTimeStep to the class attribute _d_firstTimeStep, while argument lastTimeStep is passed to the DynamicModel method _setNrTimeSteps, which updates the DynamicModel attribute _d_nrTimeSteps if the supplied value is an integer greater than zero. \\

The time loop itself is implemented in DynamicFramework.run(). This method first calls method DynamicFramework._runInitial(), which calls the initial method of userModel (defined in class DynamicModel), and then DynamicFramework._runDynamic(). This method sets a variable 'step' to equal firstTimeStep (self._userModel().firstTimeStep()) and then initiates the time loop in the form of a while loop. An annotated version of the _runDynamic method is provided below:

```python
def _runDynamic(self):
    
    # set DynamicModel attribute inDynamic to True
    self._userModel()._setInDynamic(True)
    
    # get DynamicModel attribute _d_firstTimeStep
    step = self._userModel().firstTimeStep()

    while step <= self._userModel().nrTimeSteps():
        
        self._incrementIndentLevel()
        self._atStartOfTimeStep(step)
        self._userModel()._setCurrentTimeStep(step)

        if hasattr(self._userModel(), 'dynamic')
            self.incrementIndentLevel()
            self._traceIn("dynamic")
            self._userModel().dynamic()
            self._traceOut("dynamic")
            self._decrementIndentLevel()
            
        self._timeStepFinished()
        self._decrementIndentLevel()
        step += 1

    self._userModel()._setInDynamic(False)
```

